"# Chapter 13 — A transformer block

A transformer BLOCK is not the whole transformer. It is one unit,
one 'floor' of the tower. A full transformer stacks N of these blocks
on top of each other (12 for a small model, 96 for GPT-3). Each block
has the same structure. The stack does more or less computation
depending on how tall it is.

A block has four ingredients wired together:

1. **Attention** (from chapter 12).
2. **A feed-forward network** (from chapter 8 — two-layer MLP).
3. **Residual connections** (add the input back to the output — skip
   connections).
4. **Layer normalization** (rescale so activations stay in a healthy
   range).

Every real transformer has all four. Skip any and training breaks
or gets much slower.

## The block structure

Here is the shape, in pseudocode:

```
input: x        (a sequence of embeddings, shape (seq_len, embed_dim))

output_1 = LayerNorm(x + Attention(x))
output_2 = LayerNorm(output_1 + FeedForward(output_1))
return output_2
```

The `x + Attention(x)` and `output_1 + FeedForward(output_1)` are
the residual connections. You compute a transformation, then add the
INPUT back in. That way if the transformation learned to do
'nothing', the block is still the identity — no harm done.

## Problem 1 — Layer normalization

Layer norm takes a vector and shifts + scales it so the mean is 0 and
the variance is 1, then applies a learned per-dimension gain and
bias.

```
;; Given a vector, subtract mean, divide by stddev, then apply gamma and beta.
(define (layernorm v gamma beta)
  (define d (vec/dim v))
  (define components (map (lambda (i) (vec/ref v i)) (iota d)))
  (define mean (/ (reduce + 0 components) d))
  (define centered (map (lambda (x) (- x mean)) components))
  (define variance (/ (reduce + 0 (map (lambda (c) (* c c)) centered)) d))
  (define stddev (math/sqrt (+ variance 0.00001)))   ;; 0.00001 for numerical safety
  (define normalized (map (lambda (c) (/ c stddev)) centered))
  (map (lambda (i)
         (+ (* (list-ref normalized i) (list-ref gamma i))
            (list-ref beta i)))
       (iota d)))

(define v (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define gamma (list 1 1 1 1 1))   ;; no scaling
(define beta (list 0 0 0 0 0))    ;; no shift

(display (layernorm v gamma beta))
;; A vector with mean 0 and stddev 1.
;; components: something like (-1.41 -0.71 0 0.71 1.41)
```

Layer norm keeps activations from exploding or vanishing as the
signal passes through many layers. It is applied to each token's
embedding independently — not across the whole sequence.

`gamma` and `beta` are LEARNED. Every layernorm has its own gamma
and beta vectors, trained by gradient descent like everything else.
Usually initialized to gamma=1, beta=0.

## Problem 2 — Feed-forward network

The FF part of a transformer block is exactly a 2-layer MLP with
ReLU (or GELU in some models) between the two linear layers. The
hidden dimension is usually 4x the embed dimension.

```
;; Feed-forward: input dim d, hidden dim 4d, output dim d
;; f(x) = W2 * relu(W1 * x + b1) + b2

(define (matvec rows v) (map (lambda (r) (vec/dot r v)) rows))
(define (relu-vec v)
  (vec/make (map (lambda (i)
                   (let ((x (vec/ref v i)))
                     (if (> x 0) x 0)))
                 (iota (vec/dim v)))))

(define (feed-forward W1 b1 W2 b2 x)
  (define hidden (relu-vec (vec/make (map + (matvec W1 x) b1))))
  (vec/make (map + (matvec W2 hidden) b2)))

;; Example: d=2, hidden=8
(define embed-dim 2)
(define hidden-dim 8)

(define (rand-vec n) (vec/make (map (lambda (_) (- (* (random) 0.3) 0.15)) (iota n))))
(define W1 (map (lambda (_) (rand-vec embed-dim)) (iota hidden-dim)))
(define b1 (map (lambda (_) 0.0) (iota hidden-dim)))
(define W2 (map (lambda (_) (rand-vec hidden-dim)) (iota embed-dim)))
(define b2 (map (lambda (_) 0.0) (iota embed-dim)))

(define x (list 1.0 -0.5))
(display (feed-forward W1 b1 W2 b2 x))
;; => a 2-vector (some transformed version of x)
```

FF is applied INDEPENDENTLY per token position. Each token's embedding
goes through the same feed-forward network. No mixing between
positions in the FF layer — that mixing already happened in attention.

## Problem 3 — Residual connections

Given input `x` and a transformation `T`, the residual output is
`x + T(x)`. Very simple.

```
(define (residual x transform)
  (vec/add x (transform x)))
```

Why does this matter? Two reasons.

**Gradient flow.** In a very deep network, gradients have to
backpropagate through many layers. Without residuals, the gradient
gets multiplied by many small numbers and vanishes. With residuals,
the gradient can flow around the transformation — the '+ x' path
preserves the original signal.

**Identity default.** With residuals, if a layer learns to do
nothing (weights near zero), the block is still the identity. Adding
more layers can't hurt — only help. Without residuals, an untrained
layer can DAMAGE the signal.

He et al. 2015 (ResNets) showed residuals were the key to training
very deep networks. Vaswani et al. 2017 kept them in the transformer
and they've been there ever since.

## Problem 4 — Put it together — a full block

Now compose. Attention + residual + layernorm. FF + residual +
layernorm. That is one transformer block.

```
;; Assume these are already defined:
;;   (attention-block W-q W-k W-v embeddings)
;;   (feed-forward W1 b1 W2 b2 x)
;;   (layernorm v gamma beta)

(define (transformer-block
          W-q W-k W-v          ;; attention projections
          W1-ff b1-ff W2-ff b2-ff  ;; feed-forward
          gamma1 beta1         ;; layernorm after attention
          gamma2 beta2         ;; layernorm after feed-forward
          embeddings)
  ;; 1. Attention with residual and layernorm
  (define attn-out (attention-block W-q W-k W-v embeddings))
  (define after-attn
    (map (lambda (x a) (layernorm (vec/add x a) gamma1 beta1))
         embeddings attn-out))
  ;; 2. Feed-forward with residual and layernorm
  (define ff-out
    (map (lambda (x) (feed-forward W1-ff b1-ff W2-ff b2-ff x)) after-attn))
  (define after-ff
    (map (lambda (x f) (layernorm (vec/add x f) gamma2 beta2))
         after-attn ff-out))
  after-ff)
```

Read the block. Two sub-blocks. Each is: apply transformation, add
the input back, layer-normalize. First sub-block does attention.
Second sub-block does feed-forward. Both have residuals. Both are
layer-normed.

## Problem 5 — Pre-norm vs post-norm

Above I did LayerNorm AFTER adding the residual (post-norm). Modern
transformers (GPT-2 onward) do LayerNorm BEFORE the transformation
(pre-norm):

```
;; Pre-norm variant:
;;   attn_out = x + Attention(LayerNorm(x))
;;   final   = attn_out + FeedForward(LayerNorm(attn_out))
```

Pre-norm trains more stably. Post-norm (as in the original 2017
paper) requires more careful learning-rate schedules. Both work; both
are still used. Our chapter 16 tiny LLM will use pre-norm because it
is easier to get right.

## Problem 6 — Parameter count of a block

For an embed dimension d, hidden dimension 4d, one attention head:

- Attention projections: 3 matrices of shape (d, d) plus 3 bias
  vectors = 3d^2 + 3d parameters.
- Feed-forward: (d, 4d) matrix + 4d bias + (4d, d) matrix + d bias
  = 8d^2 + 5d parameters.
- Two layernorms: 2 * 2d = 4d parameters.

Total: 11d^2 + 12d.

For d=768 (BERT-base): 11 * 589824 + 12 * 768 ≈ 6.5 million per
block. Twelve blocks: ~78 million. Plus the embedding table
(~24 million) plus the output projection (~24 million). BERT-base
was ~110 million total. Numbers check out.

For d=12288 (GPT-3): 11 * 150 million + 12 * 12288 ≈ 1.66 BILLION per
block. Ninety-six blocks: ~159 billion. Plus embeddings. GPT-3 was
175 billion. Same math, just bigger tensors.

## Capstone — Run a whole block on a small sequence

Assemble the full block and run it. We won't train — that is
chapter 16. But we can verify the shapes work end to end.

```
;; Small dimensions for a runnable demo.
(define d 4)     ;; embed dim
(define ff-hidden 8)
(define seq-len 3)

(define (rand-vec n) (vec/make (map (lambda (_) (- (* (random) 0.2) 0.1)) (iota n))))

;; Attention projections
(define W-q (map (lambda (_) (rand-vec d)) (iota d)))
(define W-k (map (lambda (_) (rand-vec d)) (iota d)))
(define W-v (map (lambda (_) (rand-vec d)) (iota d)))

;; Feed-forward
(define W1-ff (map (lambda (_) (rand-vec d)) (iota ff-hidden)))
(define b1-ff (map (lambda (_) 0.0) (iota ff-hidden)))
(define W2-ff (map (lambda (_) (rand-vec ff-hidden)) (iota d)))
(define b2-ff (map (lambda (_) 0.0) (iota d)))

;; Layernorms — gamma=1, beta=0
(define gamma1 (map (lambda (_) 1.0) (iota d)))
(define beta1  (map (lambda (_) 0.0) (iota d)))
(define gamma2 (map (lambda (_) 1.0) (iota d)))
(define beta2  (map (lambda (_) 0.0) (iota d)))

;; Sequence: three token embeddings
(define embeddings
  (list (rand-vec d) (rand-vec d) (rand-vec d)))

(define out
  (transformer-block W-q W-k W-v
                     W1-ff b1-ff W2-ff b2-ff
                     gamma1 beta1
                     gamma2 beta2
                     embeddings))

(display (length out))
;; => 3   (one output vector per input token)
(display (vec/dim (car out)))
;; => 4   (each output vector has the same dim as the input)
```

The block returned three vectors of dimension 4 from three input
vectors of dimension 4. The shape is preserved — that is the point
of the residuals. You can stack these blocks any number of times and
the shapes still line up.

## Why this matters

The transformer block is the modular unit that made deep language
models tractable. Stack 12 of them and you have BERT. Stack 96 of
them and you have GPT-3. Every block does the same thing: mix
information across positions (attention), transform per-position
(feed-forward), and add layer norm and residuals to keep gradients
flowing. You have built the atomic unit. In chapter 16 we stack a
couple and train.

## What's next

Chapter 14 solves two problems attention has:

1. **No sense of order.** Attention treats a sequence like a set —
   swap positions and the output is the same. That is fine for a bag
   of words but terrible for language, where 'dog bites man' and
   'man bites dog' mean different things. Positional encoding fixes
   this.

2. **Peeking at the future.** In a causal (next-token-prediction)
   language model, position `i` must not see positions `> i`. Causal
   masking enforces this during training. Otherwise the model just
   copies the answer and doesn't learn.
")
